On Friday 1 September, Hong Kong has issued a T9 storm warning signal for Typhoon Saola. It is possible a higher warning signal could be issued within the next 24 hours.
Flights have been affected so check with your airline ahead of travel and be prepared to change your plans. Other transportation services in Hong Kong have been suspended. Travellers are advised to remain indoors until the storm warning signal has reduced. For the latest information check the Hong Kong Observatory website.
See our tropical cyclones page for advice about how to prepare effectively and what to do if you’re likely to be affected by a hurricane or tropical cyclone.
The typhoon season in Hong Kong normally runs from April to October. Typhoons sometimes hit Hong Kong and may cause flooding and landslides. Local warnings are issued in advance. Public offices shut down when the ‘Typhoon 8’ signal is hoisted.
You should monitor local and international weather updates from the World Meteorological Organisation (WMO) and Hong Kong Observatory. See Tropical Cyclones page for advice on what to do if you’re caught up in a storm.
